docs.abstract: A $9 million deal for the use of artificial intelligence technology has fractured the internet giant’s work force and risks driving away top engineering talent.
docs.snippet: A $9 million deal for the use of artificial intelligence technology has fractured the internet giant’s work force and risks driving away top engineering talent.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Fei-Fei Li is among the brightest stars in the burgeoning field of artificial intelligence, somehow managing to hold down two demanding jobs simultaneously: head of Stanford University’s A.I. lab and chief scientist for A.I. at Google Cloud, one of the search giant’s most promising enterprises.

headline.main: How a Pentagon Contract Became an Identity Crisis for Google
headline.print_headline: Pentagon Deal Creates Schism Within Google

byline.original: By Scott Shane, Cade Metz and Daisuke Wakabayashi

docs.abstract: Hackers can exploit two major security flaws in microprocessors running virtually all machines on Earth. What do you do now?
docs.snippet: Hackers can exploit two major security flaws in microprocessors running virtually all machines on Earth. What do you do now?
docs.lead_paragraph: On Wednesday, a group of security experts revealed two security flaws that affect nearly all microprocessors, the digital brains of the world’s computers. These flaws, called Meltdown and Spectre, could allow hackers to lift passwords, photos, documents and other data from smartphones, PCs and the cloud computing services that many businesses rely on.

headline.main: What You Need to Do Because of Flaws in Computer Chips
headline.print_headline: The Lowdown on the Flaws in Computer Chips

byline.original: By Cade Metz and Brian X. Chen

docs.abstract: Powered by sales of its iPhone X, the tech giant reported another strong quarter and defied fears that consumers wouldn’t buy the pricey devices.
docs.snippet: Powered by sales of its iPhone X, the tech giant reported another strong quarter and defied fears that consumers wouldn’t buy the pricey devices.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Since Apple said in January that it would  bring back most of the $252 billion it held abroad under the new tax law, investors have wondered what the company would do with the enormous cash pile. On Tuesday, those investors learned that they are in line for a big chunk of the money.

headline.main: Apple Says It Will Buy Back $100 Billion in Stock
headline.print_headline: Apple, Awash in Cash, Buys Back More Stock

docs.abstract: BMW and Mercedes-Benz rebuffed Apple’s overtures for a self-driving car partnership, according to people familiar with the talks.
docs.snippet: BMW and Mercedes-Benz rebuffed Apple’s overtures for a self-driving car partnership, according to people familiar with the talks.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Apple once had grand aspirations to build its own electric self-driving car and lead the next generation of transportation. Over time, the tech giant’s ambitions ran into reality.

headline.main: Apple, Spurned by Others, Signs Deal With Volkswagen for Driverless Cars
headline.print_headline: Volkswagen to Join Apple For Autonomous Project

docs.abstract: Video creators, including Nasim Aghdam, have been complaining for months about YouTube’s pulling their ads. Then one of them went to company headquarters with a gun.

docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — The authorities believe a woman who shot three people at YouTube’s headquarters before killing herself on Tuesday was angered by the social media outlet’s policies.

docs.abstract: The e-commerce giant has won two patents for a tracking technology that can nudge a human hand in the right direction — toward a warehouse bin, say.
docs.snippet: The e-commerce giant has won two patents for a tracking technology that can nudge a human hand in the right direction — toward a warehouse bin, say.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — What if your employer made you wear a wristband that tracked your every move, and that even nudged you via vibrations when it judged that you were doing something wrong?

headline.main: If Workers Slack Off, the Wristband Will Know. (And Amazon Has a Patent for It.)
headline.print_headline: Track Hands Of Workers? Amazon Has Patents for It

docs.abstract: As calls for gun bans intensify after the Parkland shooting, some sellers proudly display AR-15 semiautomatic rifles but say they support some limits.
docs.snippet: As calls for gun bans intensify after the Parkland shooting, some sellers proudly display AR-15 semiautomatic rifles but say they support some limits.
docs.lead_paragraph: TAMPA, Fla. — The lines stretched out the door this weekend at a gun show in Tampa, Fla., as thousands of potential buyers and the merely curious waited for their turn to browse booths stocked with the latest firearms, ammunition, customizable holsters and patriotic paraphernalia.

headline.main: Lines Out the Door and Strong Sales at Tampa Gun Show
headline.print_headline: Strong Sales at Gun Show, but Cracks in Solidarity

docs.abstract: The bank will no longer lend money to manufacturers of firearms like the AR-15, which have been used in multiple mass shootings.
docs.snippet: The bank will no longer lend money to manufacturers of firearms like the AR-15, which have been used in multiple mass shootings.
docs.lead_paragraph: Bank of America will stop lending money to gun manufacturers that make military-inspired firearms for civilian use, such as the AR-15-style rifles that have been used in multiple mass shootings, a company executive said Tuesday.

headline.main: Bank of America to Stop Financing Makers of Military-Style Guns
headline.print_headline: Gunmakers Facing Limits From Another Major Lender
